The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Sunday, July 04, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Santiniketan, July 3: Visva-Bharati authorities have taken the initiative to digitise the collection of manuscripts at Rabindra Bhavan. According to university sources, the Bengali department is on the job and the manuscripts would be available on the official V-B website. 				 																																	The manuscripts will be available on the website and can be downloaded as reference material. More than 10,000 pages of these manuscripts have already been scanned, the official said. Vice-chancellor Sujit Basu said it would stop people from taking them out from the library. 				 																																	Calcutta: The chairperson of the M.P. Birla Group, Priyamvada Birla, passed away here on Saturday after a short illness. She took over the stewardship of the group after the death of her husband, M.P. Birla, in 1990.				 																																	Balurghat (South Dinajpur): The state electricity board has started a probe against two employees of its unit here. The duo allegedly gave illegal power connections to shops, commercial organisations and residential buildings. Two officials of SEBs vigilance sector said they had received proof against illegal connections given by the two. 				 																																	Calcutta: Fifteen fire tenders were rushed to extinguish a blaze in the godown of a consumer electrical goods company at Jinjira bazar of Taratolla around 8 pm. Deputy commissioner of police .P. Gupta said the fire might have caused by an electrical short circuit. 				 																																	Barrackpore (North 24-Parganas): Sushanta Mondal, a quack and a CPM leader in Bijpur, was arrested on Friday night for allegedly molesting a 14-year-old girl. On the pretext of examining the girl, complaining of stomach ache, he took her to his chamber and molested her. 
